Google Data Analytics Case Study - Cyclistic Bike Share

Liong Teng Lap

2023-01-12

Introduction

The following case study sets the scene where I am working as a junior data analyst in the marketing analytics team at a bike share company in Chicago named Cyclistic.

The stakehholders involved are:

  • The director of marketing and my manager: responsible for the development of campaigns and initiatives to promote the bike-sharing program, which may include email, social media and other channels.
  • Cyclistic executive team: Detail-oriented executive team that decides the approval of recommended marketing program.

The director of marketing believes that the companys future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Hence, the marketing analytics team are tasked to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently and design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members.

The data analysis life cycle used for the case study are made up of 6 phases:

  • Phase 1: ASK
    • Define problem to solve.
  • Phase 2: PREPARE
    • Collect, manage and organize data for upcoming analysis process.
  • Phase 3: PROCESS
    • Clean data to eliminate error and inaccuracies.
  • Phase 4: ANALYZE
    • Discover relationships and patterns in data.
  • Phase 5: SHARE
    • Summarize findings and create data visualization to better understand findings.
  • Phase 6: ACT
    • Provide recommendations based on insights so stakeholder can make better informed decisions.

Phase 1: ASK

Business goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members

Questions asked to guide future marketing program:

  • How do annual and member riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?
    • When are casual and member riders most active?
    • Which is the preferred bike among users?
    • Where do users ride to the most?

With the insights obtain, the following questions would be:

  • Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual membership?
  • How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to member riders?

Phase 2: PREPARE

1. Data Organization

There are 12 CSV files where each CSV file represent a month of the Cyclistic bike share dataset, starting from Dec-2021 to Nov-2022.

Since the CSV files are huge, with more than 200,000 rows of data each file, all the CSV files were stored in the BigQuery database in the form of table. Working with SQL instead of Spreadsheet for huge dataset will be more efficient where data can be cleaned and transformed in a faster and easier manner.

Shown in the diagram below, the monthly tables are stored in the cyclistic_dataset.

2. Data Source credibility

The dataset used for Cyclistic, a fictional company, is an open data made by Motivate International Inc., under this license. The data is unbias as it is inclusive of sample group from people with disabilities and is representative of the population as a whole.

Phase 3: PROCESS

1. Cleaning & Transforming data with SQL BigQuery

Data cleaning is important as dirty data will cause inaccurate analysis. Generally, there are 5 types of dirty data, such as :

  • Duplicate data
  • Outdated data
  • Missing data (NULLS)
  • Incorrect data
  • Inconsistent data

The data cleaning process will be tackling each of the dirty data.

1.1. NULL Checking using SQL Query

The NULL checking process was done using the Jan_22 table where NULLS were identified for start_station_name and end_station_name.

Hence, a few sample of the start_station_names and end_station_names coordinate (start_lat, start_lng) and (end_lat, end_lng) were used to test if the station names can be retrieved using the coordinates.

1.1.1. start_station_name tracking

1.1.2. end_station_name tracking

1.1.3. start_station_name & end_station_name tracking findings, & NULL deletion decision

From the start_station_name NULL check, it is shown that Most of the station names with the stated coordinates remain NULL except for (41.97, -87.7) which shows 3 different station names:

  • NULL
  • California Ave & Winona St
  • N Shore Channel Trail & Argyle Ave

The same coordinate returned 3 inconsistent results. This may be due to:

  • The stated coordinate is a small area which may consist of several station
  • Bikes that were used without stations name (NULL) may be due to the bike being parked at inappropriate location, not by the station.

Since the business task is to create a marketing strategy to convert casual riders to members, having a station name may be important for advertising purposes, hence, observations with NULL station names shall be deleted as part of the cleaning process.

1.2. Table combination, field selection & cleaning

The query shown below combines all relevant table into a bigger table to be cleaned and transformed. As concluded previously, NULL station names will be filtered out from the combined table, DISTINCT function to eliminate duplicate data, and additional field such as ride_duration_sec and day_of_week will be added for analysis usage.

With the above query, the data is free from:

  • Duplicate data
  • Missing data
  • Outdated data (since it is a 1 year time-bound analysis)

The rest of the data checking and cleaning will be done in section 2 with R.

1.3. Data organization for Clean data

The table executed from the query in section 2.2 is then stored in a seperate dataset named Cyclistic_clean_dataset with the table name Dec21_to_Nov22_R1.

2.2. Accessing BigQuery with R

Since the dataset is huge with about 4.4 million observations, it was decided to store the dataset in BigQuery database table rather than downloading it locally as it will be less efficient working with a CSV file this large.

Hence, in order to access the dataset from BigQuery, the code below are used to connect RStudio with BigQuery.

Note that this is the 1st revision of the dataset after data cleaning.

Table name : Dec21_to_Nov22_R1

# Link R with BigQuery Project ID
projectid = "top-virtue-373612"

# Set query
sql <- "SELECT * FROM `top-virtue-373612.Cyclistic_clean_dataset.Dec21_to_Nov22_R1`"

# Store BigQuery table in a variable
bikeshare <- bq_project_query(projectid, sql)

From the summary, it was found that the :

  1. The minimum ride duration is in negative value, -10122.
  2. The maximum ride duration is 2061244 seconds, which is about 572.6 hours.

The dataset was further cleaned using R by: * Filtering out negative ride duration. * Filtering out ride_duration_sec that is more than 86400 assuming a 1-day pass is a 24-hour pass. (24 hours = 86400 seconds)

biketrip_tb_r1 <- biketrip_tb %>% 
  filter(ride_duration_sec > 0) %>% 
  filter(ride_duration_sec <= 86400)

Phase 4 & 5: ANALYZE & SHARE

To start it off, the customer base of Cyclistic bike share was analyzed to find out how many users are there, in terms of member riders and casual riders.

total_users <- biketrip_tb_r1 %>% 
  group_by(member_casual) %>% 
  summarise(rider_count = n())
  
head(total_users)
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   member_casual rider_count
##   <chr>               <int>
## 1 casual            1771453
## 2 member            2638385
total_users %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = "", y = rider_count, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(rider_count/sum(rider_count)*100), "%")), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#F8766D", "#00BFC4")) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, fill = NULL, title = "Cyclistic Casual & Member User Percentage") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.line = element_blank(),
        axis.text = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

It was found that majority of the customers are already subscribed as a member with 60% member riders and 40% unsubscribed casual riders. In order to achieve the business objective of converting more casual riders to member riders, the dataset was further explored to better understand the users behavior.

Generally, the main question for this analysis is to answer How are annual members and casual riders using Cyclistic bikes differently?, which would then lead to more informed decision on designing the right strategy of increasing membership subscription. Hence, to draw a conclusion for the main question, 3 of the following questions were analyzed to justify the main question:

  • When are casual and member riders most active?
  • Which is the preferred bike among users?
  • Where do users ride to the most?

Chart 1.3: Amount of riders hourly from Monday to Friday over a period of 12 Months

From Chart 1.1 and 1.2, it is shown that casual riders uses the bike share service most during Saturdays and Sundays, whereas member riders are more active during the weekdays. This may be due to casual riders uses the service more for leisure or sightseeing during the weekends whereas member riders uses it to commute to work on the weekdays.

To justify the assumption where casual riders uses the service for leisure and member riders for commuting, the relationship between the start time and the dataset was manipulated to add another column start_time_hr to fold the time where user start using the bike in hour, to observe at which time of the day is the bike share service most active between casual and member riders throughout the week.

# Adding another field to store start time(hour) 

biketrip_tb_r1_time <- biketrip_tb_r1 %>%  #manipulated table to be stored in biketrip_tb_r2_time
  mutate(start_time_hr = hour(ymd_hms(biketrip_tb_r1$started_at)))

Chart 1.3 shows that:

  • Casual riders:
    • Peaks around 5pm on weekdays while remaining low for the throughout the day.
    • Very active during the weekends where riders remains high from 11am to 6pm.
    • Casual riders are generally higher than member riders on weekends and lower on weekdays.
  • Member riders:
    • Peaks around 8am and 5pm on weekdays while remaining low for the rest of the day.
    • No peak is observed at 8am during the weekends.
    • Remain constantly high from 11am to 6pm on weekends but generally lesser than the amount of casual riders.

The yellow highlighted peaks supports the hypothesize where member uses the bike for commuting where 8am is most likely when users ride to work, and 5pm when user ride back home.

Further exploration will be done to find out what casual riders uses the bike for.

Moving on, Chart 1.4 shows that the top 3 months with most active riders for both casual and member riders are from June to August. Based on the annual Chicago average temperature by NOAA (National Oceanic And Atmospheric Administration) shown below, June to August is also the top 3 warmest months throughout the year as it represents the Summer season in America.

Hence, it can be said that there is a correlation between the temperature and amount of active rider where as the temperature gets warmer, the amount of rider gets larger.

From Chart 1.1 and 1.2, it is observed that:

  • Classic bike remains as the most used bike among the casual and member riders, followed by electric bike and docked bike.
    • This may be due to using classic bike can be treated as a form of exercise and a healthier option compared to electric bike, and also not having to worry about battery running out.
    • Docked bike having the least preference may be due to not being as aesthetically pleasing and comfortable as compared to classical bike, even though it works the same as a classical bike.
      • Additional data will be needed to justify bike preference in a form of survey as current data is limited.

4. Summary of analysis

Note: Data is based on Chicago where standard U.S. business hours are 9am to 5pm, Monday through Friday.

From the trend and pattern observed, it can be concluded that :

  • Casual riders uses the Cyclistic bikes for leisure, exercise and sightseeing
    • Pattern from Chart 1.1, Chart 1.2 and Chart 1.3 suggest that casual riders are very active on weekends throughout the day and peaks around 5pm on weekdays after working hours.
      • Chart 1.2 shows that amount of casual riders never outgrow member riders on weekdays, but does outgrows member riders on weekends.
      • While pairing Chart 1.3 and Chart 3.2, both findings suggest that casual riders peaks around 5pm on weekdays for leisure or cycling exercise around tourists attraction areas.
      • Chart 3.1 further supports the the statement where the top 10 routes most taken by casual riders are also around tourists attraction areas.
    • Average ride duration for casual riders are long for about 35 minutes.
  • Member riders uses Cyclistic bikes for commuting as well as leisure
    • Pattern shown from Chart 1.1, Chart 1.2 and Chart 1.3 suggest that member riders are more active on weekdays and peaks around 8am and 5pm on weekdays are highly due to commuting to and from work or school.
      • Chart 1.3 also shows that subsided peak can be seen during weekends at 8am where most users will not be waking up early to commute during non working days.
      • While pairing Chart 1.3 with Chart 3.4, both findings suggest that member riders peak start time uses the routes between housing areas, commercial areas and Universities during 8am and 5pm as well.
      • Chart 3.3 further supports the the statement where the top 10 routes most taken by member riders are also around housing areas, commercial areas and universities.
    • The constant amount of riders from 11am to 6pm on weekends from Chart 1.3 suggest that members uses Cyclistic bike for leisure as well.
    • Members average ride duration for top 10 most used routes are short for about 5 minutes.
  • The most active season for the bike share service is during the Summer, from June to August
    • As shown in Chart 1.4, both casual and member riders top 3 highest count of riders are from the month of June to August where temperature are the warmest.
    • Trend can be seen where as temperature gets warmer, amount of rider gets larger.
  • Classic bike is most preferred among casual and member riders
    • Chart 2.1 and 2.2 shows that throughout the days and months, classic bike remains on top among electric and docked bike.
    • It is assumed that classic bike is most preferred due to it being a healthier and worry-free choice compared to the electric bike with a finite mileage per charge, and more aesthetic pleasing compared to docked bike.
      • The data is limited to justify the bike preference.

Phase 6: ACT

Recommendations

Business objective: To convert casual riders into annual members

Note: Assuming the company already has their own Cyclistic bike share mobile application for used for subscription, bike location and duration tracking.

  • Create an accumulative point reward system (eg.: Cyclistic-coin), for members that cycle more than 30 minutes where Cyclistic-coin can be used to redeem other digital wallet credit or used directly.
    • As seen from the trends, the average ride duration of casual riders are about 35 minutes on average from the top 10 routes, and an average of 29 minutes from 5pm weekdays ride. Hence, implementing a point rewarding system may attract casual riders to subscribe for membership where they can earn and ride almost every day.
  • Partner with F&Bs around tourist attraction spots where goods can be bought directly using Cyclistic-coin.
    • Since casual riders tend to ride around tourist attraction locations, buying snacks or drinks are anticipated to be a common thing to do. Hence, by becoming a member, they can then earn the Cyclistic-coin to purchase these goods instead.
    • Partnering with tourist attraction shops helps promote the Cyclistic membership scheme as well as helping out the business of these shops, a win-win scenario.
  • Partnering with tourist attraction sites where Cyclistic member are entitled for discount during weekends and Summer.
    • Partnering with attraction sites such as the Navy Pier and Chicagos Children Museum located at Streeter Dr & Grand Ave, Millenium Park Ice Rink at Millenium Park, and Shedd Aquarium where Cyclistic members are entitled for a discounted entrance fee during weekends and Summer, where both weekends and Summer are peak seasons for Cyclistic bike share.
  • Create members weekly or monthly challenges for reward earning and increasing social media presence.
    • Challenges can be such as taking and posting a picture online of the bike at selected tourist attraction spot to earn Cyclistic-coin.
    • Posting pictures of Cyclistic bikes can help promote online presence.
    • Company can also validate and re-post pictures taken by users on selected social media platform to increase engagement.
  • Organize cycling marathon during the summer.
    • Non-members who attend the cycling marathon will be offered a discounted rate on annual member subscription that will last until the following Summer, while members who participated can earn Cyclistic-coin and also be offered a discounted annual membership rate for the following year.
      • This create an opportunity to continuously organize cycling marathon with paid entrance fee every Summer and users are able to renew their annual membership and at discounted rate.
    • Big events such as this can attract a lot of attentions online and locally which amplifies advertising power to audiences.
